1 Project Background¶

1.1 Problem¶

This challenge involves solving a binary image classification problem using convolutional neural networks (CNNs), where the task is to identify metastatic cancer in small image patches extracted from larger digital pathology slides.

The dataset is based on a cleaned version of the PatchCamelyon (PCam) dataset, a benchmark derived from the Camelyon16 challenge. Each image patch is labeled as:

1 → contains metastatic tissue

0 → benign (non-metastatic)

Project Data type, size, dimension, structure¶

  • 1 csv file listing the image ID with its Binary label for testing (ground truth)
  • 1 set of training images (count 220025)
  • 1 set of test images (count 57458)

Images size & Dimension¶

  • Input: RGB image patches (coloured images)
  • Shape: 96 x 96 x 3
  • Type: .tif
  • Label: Binary (0 or 1)

Each images has the ID as its filename. The ID can be referenced back to the .csv file for the ground truth labelling for the training data. The test images also has the filename as Image ID while no labels are provided.

1.2 Project Goal¶

The primary goal of this project is to develop a Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) model that can accurately classify whether a given microscopic image patch contains metastatic cancer tissue (label 1) or benign tissue (label 0). This is a binary classification task based on high-resolution histopathology image patches derived from whole-slide scans.

The model should be capable of learning discriminative features from the provided 96x96x3 RGB image inputs, generalizing to unseen data with strong performance in terms of classification metrics such as accuracy, AUC, or F1-score.

2 Data Cleaning¶

2.1 Reasons¶

  • Check for Missing or Corrupted Images

A missing or unreadable image can cause your training loop to crash. Should try loading all images and see if the script can open all of them and discard those images that cannot be opened.

  • Class Label Distribution

Histogram to check if the binary labels are distributed evenly on both labels to prevent biased model

  • Check for images format

Check to see if all images in both training and test follow the standardised 96 x 96 x 3 RGB format

  • Check for label consistency

The .csv files may contain labels other than 0 and 1

  • Check for image duplication

Duplicated images, especially those that exist in both test and train set could cause data leakage affecting the final model.

def show_sample_images(folder_path, title):
    sample_images = random.sample(os.listdir(folder_path), 6)
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 6, figsize=(18, 4))

Image Transform for Data Augmentation¶

The code defines image transformations used for data augmentation during training and consistent preprocessing during validation.

The train_transform applies random transformations such as rotation, horizontal flipping, and color jittering to artificially increase dataset diversity. This helps the model generalize better by exposing it to varied versions of the same images.

The val_transform applies only resizing and normalization to maintain consistency and evaluate model performance on unaltered validation data.

Both of the transform will normalizeimage to center pixels near 0 to stabilize model training.

In [8]:
def set_seed(seed=42):
    random.seed(seed)
    np.random.seed(seed)
    torch.manual_seed(seed)
    torch.cuda.manual_seed(seed)
    torch.cuda.manual_seed_all(seed)  # if using multi-GPU

    torch.backends.cudnn.deterministic = True
    torch.backends.cudnn.benchmark = False

    os.environ['PYTHONHASHSEED'] = str(seed)

Dataset Container Preparation¶

This code sets up a custom PyTorch data pipeline for image classification.

  • Adopt GPU performance for the data

  • Data is split into training and validation sets using stratified sampling to maintain label balance (80% training, 20% validation)

  • Two DataLoader instances are created—one for training and one for validation—each with batch size 64.

  • The ImageDataset class loads image paths and labels from the "df_subset_train", processes .tif images using OpenCV, converts BGR to RGB, and applies optional transformations. The dataset also maps image IDs to indices for internal tracking and returns tensors in the correct format for model input.

In [9]:
class ImageDataset(Dataset):
    def __init__(self, dataframe, image_dir,transform=None):
        self.df = dataframe.reset_index(drop=True)
        self.image_dir = image_dir
        self.transform = transform
        self.original_shape = None
        
        #Create "label:index" & "index:label" mapping
        self.id_to_index = {id: index for index, id in enumerate(self.df['id'].unique())}
        self.index_to_id = {index: id for id, index in self.id_to_index.items()}
        
        #Create a new column in dataframe for label index
        self.df['index'] = self.df['id'].map(self.id_to_index)
        
    # Let Dataloader to get length of dataframe
    def __len__(self):
        return self.df.shape[0]

    # Let Dataloader to get item by index call
    def __getitem__(self, index):
        # Load image and pair up index label
        img_id = self.df.loc[index, 'id']
        img_label = self.df.loc[index, 'label']
        
        # Read Image
        img_path = os.path.join(self.image_dir, img_id) + ".tif"
        image = cv2.imread(img_path)
        if self.original_shape is None:
            self.original_shape = image.shape
            
        # Preprocess image: BGR to RGB
        image = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)
        
        # Ensure image size is 96x96
        image = cv2.resize(image, (96, 96), interpolation=cv2.INTER_AREA)

        # Apply transformations if provided
        if self.transform:
            image = self.transform(image)
        else:
            # Center the image data to -1 to 1 range
            image = image.astype('float32') / 255.0
            image = (image - 0.5) / 0.5
            
            # Match PyTorch input format: Channel x Height x Width
            image = torch.from_numpy(image).permute(2, 0, 1)
        
        return image, torch.tensor(img_label, dtype=torch.long)

CNN Architecture¶

This code defines a convolutional neural network (CNN) architecture in PyTorch using a modular and dynamic design approach.

The CNN_model class inherits from nn.Module and builds a deep convolutional feature extractor followed by fully connected layers for classification. Effort has been made to structure the convolutional layer definitions using configuration lists, allowing easy adjustment of filter sizes, strides, padding, and number of layers. This dynamic setup makes the architecture flexible and easily tunable for different datasets and tasks.

For convolutional layers¶

  • Dynamically constructs convolutional layers using configurable lists for number of filters, kernel sizes, strides, and padding

  • Uses nn.ModuleList to store sequential convolutional blocks, each with Conv2D, BatchNorm, and ReLU

  • Applies stride-based downsampling instead of pooling to reduce spatial dimensions

For fully connected layers¶

  • Automatically computes the final feature map size to determine the input dimension for the fully connected layers

  • Fully connected classifier consists of multiple linear layers with batch normalization, ReLU activations, and dropout for regularization

In [10]:
# Define CNN Model Architecture
class CNN_model(nn.Module):
    
    #Set Up model architecture
    def __init__(self, layer_config,num_classes,init_channel=3,input_size = 96, dropout = 0.5):
        
        super(CNN_model, self).__init__()
        self.num_classes = num_classes
        self.init_channel = init_channel
        self.input_size = input_size
        self.dropout = dropout
        
        self.nr_filters = layer_config['nr_filters']
        self.feature_size = layer_config['feature_size']
        filter_sizes = layer_config['filter_sizes']
        padding_values = layer_config['padding_values']
        stride_values = layer_config['stride_values']
        
        # Layer dynamic configuration 
        self.layers_config = []
        for i in range(len(self.nr_filters)):
            config = {
                'in_channels': init_channel if i == 0 else self.nr_filters[i - 1],
                'out_channels': self.nr_filters[i],
                'kernel_size': filter_sizes[i],
                'padding': padding_values[i],
                'stride': stride_values[i]
            }
            self.layers_config.append(config)
            
        # Define layers based on configuration
        self.define_conv_layers()
        self.define_fc_layers()
    
    # Define Convolutional layers
    def define_conv_layers(self):
        
        self.conv_layers = nn.ModuleList()
        current_size = self.input_size
        
        for i,cfg in enumerate(self.layers_config):
            block = nn.Sequential(
                nn.Conv2d(cfg['in_channels'], cfg['out_channels'],
                        kernel_size=cfg['kernel_size'],
                        padding=cfg['padding'],
                        stride=cfg['stride']),
                nn.BatchNorm2d(cfg['out_channels']),
                nn.ReLU(inplace=True),
            )
            self.conv_layers.append(block)
            
            current_size = ((current_size + 2 * cfg['padding'] - cfg['kernel_size']) // cfg['stride']) + 1
            
        self.final_feature_dim = self.nr_filters[-1] * current_size * current_size
        
    # Define Fully connected layers
    def define_fc_layers(self):  
        dp = self.dropout
        f_size = self.feature_size
        final_f_dim = self.final_feature_dim
        nr_class = self.num_classes
        
        self.classifier = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(final_f_dim, f_size),
            nn.BatchNorm1d(f_size),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Dropout(dp),

            nn.Linear(f_size, f_size),
            nn.BatchNorm1d(f_size),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Dropout(dp),

            nn.Linear(f_size, f_size //2),
            nn.BatchNorm1d(f_size //2),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Dropout(dp),
            
            nn.Linear(f_size//2, nr_class)
        )
            
    #Execute forward pass based on architecture
    def forward(self, x):
        
        # Run Convolutional layers
        for block in self.conv_layers:
            x = block(x)
        
        # Flatten the tensor for the fully connected layers
        x = x.view(x.size(0), -1)
        
        # Run Fully connected layers
        x = self.classifier(x)
        return x

Model Training and Evaluation Loop¶

This function defines the full training and evaluation loop for a CNN model using PyTorch.

It trains the model over a defined number of epochs, tracks loss and accuracy, and evaluates performance on both training and validation datasets. It also applies a learning rate scheduler step at the end of each epoch to adjust the learning rate dynamically.

In summary:

  • Performs per-epoch training and validation with loss and accuracy tracking
  • Uses torch.argmax for prediction and computes F1-score and accuracy via scikit-learn
  • Stores metrics (losses and accuracies) for both training and validation
  • Applies scheduler.step() for learning rate scheduling after each epoch
  • Set the same seed for training
  • Early stopping applied
In [11]:
# Model Configuration
def train_and_evaluate_model(model,optimizer,criterion,scheduler,nr_epoches = 20, warmup_scheduler = None, early_stopping_patience = None):
    
    # Training and Validation Loop
    train_losses = []
    val_losses = []
    train_f1_score = []
    val_f1_score = []
    
    best_val_f1 = 0
    best_model_wts = copy.deepcopy(model.state_dict())
    
    model_index = 0
    no_improve_epochs = 0
    
    for epoch in range(nr_epoches):
        
        # Training Loop
        avg_train_loss, train_f1, train_acc = training_loop(model,optimizer,criterion,train_loader)
        train_losses.append(avg_train_loss)
        train_f1_score.append(train_f1)
        
        # evaluation Loop
        avg_val_loss, val_f1, val_acc = evaluation_loop(model,criterion,val_loader)
        val_losses.append(avg_val_loss)
        val_f1_score.append(val_f1)
        
        # Print epoch results
        print(f'Epoch [{epoch+1}/{nr_epoches}], Train Loss: {avg_train_loss:.4f}, Val Loss: {avg_val_loss:.4f}')
        print(f'Epoch [{epoch+1}/{nr_epoches}], Train F1: {train_f1:.4f}, Val F1: {val_f1:.4f}')
        print(f'Epoch [{epoch+1}/{nr_epoches}], Train Acc: {train_acc:.4f}, Val Acc: {val_acc:.4f}')
        
        # Save best model weights
        if val_f1 > best_val_f1:
            best_val_f1 = val_f1
            best_model_wts = copy.deepcopy(model.state_dict())
            model_index = epoch
            no_improve_epochs = 0
        else:
            if early_stopping_patience is not None:
                no_improve_epochs += 1
            
        # learning rate decay
        if warmup_scheduler is not None:
            warmup_scheduler.step()
        scheduler.step()
        
        print (f'Early stopping counter: {no_improve_epochs}')
        print ('-'*50)
        
        # Early Stopping trigger
        if no_improve_epochs >= early_stopping_patience:
            print(f'Early stopping at epoch {epoch+1} — no improvement for {early_stopping_patience} epochs.')
            break

    model.load_state_dict(best_model_wts)
        
    return model,model_index,train_losses, val_losses, train_f1_score, val_f1_score

# Training Loop
def training_loop(model,optimizer,criterion,train_loader):
    model.train()
    total_train_loss  = 0
    train_preds = []
    train_targets = []
    
    for images, labels in train_loader:
        
        # Move data to device
        images = images.to(device, non_blocking=True)
        labels = labels.to(device, non_blocking=True)

        # Forward pass  
        optimizer.zero_grad()
        outputs = model(images)
        
        # Compute loss
        loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
        loss.backward()

        # Update weights
        optimizer.step()
        total_train_loss  += loss.item()
        
        # Get predictions
        preds = torch.argmax(outputs, dim=1)
        train_preds.append(preds.cpu())
        train_targets.append(labels.cpu())
    
    avg_train_loss = total_train_loss / len(train_loader)

    # Compute accuracy and F1 for training set
    train_preds = torch.cat(train_preds).numpy()
    train_targets = torch.cat(train_targets).numpy()
    train_f1 = f1_score(train_targets, train_preds)
    train_acc = accuracy_score(train_targets, train_preds)
    
    return avg_train_loss, train_f1, train_acc

# Evaluation Loop
def evaluation_loop(model,criterion,val_loader):
    model.eval()
    total_val_loss = 0
    all_preds = []
    all_targets = []
    with torch.no_grad():
        for images, labels in val_loader:
            
            # Move data to device
            images = images.to(device, non_blocking=True)
            labels = labels.to(device, non_blocking=True)

            # Compute validation loss
            outputs = model(images)
            loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
            total_val_loss += loss.item()
            
            # Get predictions
            preds = torch.argmax(outputs, dim=1)
            all_preds.append(preds.cpu())
            all_targets.append(labels.cpu())
    
    avg_val_loss = total_val_loss / len(val_loader)
    
    # Compute accuracy and F1 for validation set
    all_preds = torch.cat(all_preds).numpy()
    all_targets = torch.cat(all_targets).numpy()
    val_f1 = f1_score(all_targets, all_preds)
    val_acc = accuracy_score(all_targets, all_preds)
    
    return avg_val_loss, val_f1, val_acc

# Weight Initialization Function
def init_weights_xavier(m):
    if isinstance(m, nn.Linear) or isinstance(m, nn.Conv2d):
        nn.init.xavier_uniform_(m.weight)
        if m.bias is not None:
            nn.init.zeros_(m.bias)

Model Training and Hyperparameters Tuning¶

This script defines and trains a convolutional neural network (CNN) using PyTorch with a custom architecture and hyperparameters.

Xavier Initialization¶

A function init_weights_xavier is defined to apply Xavier uniform initialization to all nn.Linear and nn.Conv2d layers. Bias terms are initialized to zero if they exist. This helps stabilize the training process by maintaining variance across layers.

CNN Architecture Configuration¶

A dictionary CNN_layer_config specifies the architecture of the CNN. It defines:

  • nr_filters: Number of filters for each convolutional layer.

  • filter_sizes: Kernel size for each convolutional layer (all 3×3).

  • padding_values: Padding applied to each layer (all 1).

  • stride_values: Stride values, alternating between 1 and 2 for downsampling.

  • feature_size: Final flattened feature size before the classifier.

Hyperparameters¶

  • nr_epoches: Total number of training epochs.

  • dropout: Dropout rate in the network to prevent overfitting.

  • weight_decay: L2 regularization coefficient in the optimizer.

  • learning_rate: Base learning rate for the optimizer.

  • scheduler_T_Max: Number of epochs for a full cosine cycle in the learning rate scheduler.

Initialization, Loss, Optimizer and Scheduler¶

  • Weights are initialized with Xavier uniform initialization. CrossEntropyLoss is used for classification.

  • The Adam optimizer includes weight decay for regularization.

  • A cosine annealing scheduler adjusts the learning rate cyclically, improving convergence over epochs.

Hyperparameter Tuning Trial A [1st model] (2,000 number of train samples)¶

Trial A uses a simple 6-layer CNN architecture with a small number of filters as a baseline. To save computation, it is trained on a small subset of the data (2000 samples) to ensure the pipeline works correctly. A low learning rate of 1e-5 is used, with no dropout or weight decay applied, aiming to observe the model’s basic learning capability.

Conclusion on Model A (2000 samples)

The 1st Trial model (Model A) shows moderate learning behavior with the following observations:

Steady but slow training progress

  • Train loss decreased from 0.81 → 0.74

  • Train F1 increased from 0.49 → 0.56

  • Train accuracy improved from 0.52 → 0.58

Gradual validation improvement

  • Val loss decreased from 0.81 → 0.74

  • Val F1 increased from 0.49 → 0.60

  • Val accuracy improved from 0.52 → 0.61

Low learning rate impact

  • Learning rate at 1e-5 resulted in slow convergence

  • Model improves gradually, but maybe a higher learning rate will make the model converge faster (worth trying)

No overfitting observed

  • Val F1 moves in sync with train F1

  • Slight flutcuation observed, but generally both validation and training accuracy rise together

Next Step for this model

  • Explore deeper architecture or attention layers to boost capacity and representation

  • Increase epoches to observe improvement on training time

  • Add dropout & weight decay to stabilize the model a little bit

Hyperparameter Tuning Trial B [2nd model] (2,000 number of train samples)¶

Amendment to model

  • Deepen the CNN architecture with 8 concolution layers and using stride values in a 1,2,1,2,... patterm

  • Increase number of epoches to 60

  • Added dropout and weight decay to 0.1 & 0.00001 respectively

  • scheduler_T_Max to match nr_epoches

Conclusion on Model B (2000 samples)

Consistent training progress

  • Train loss decreased from 0.82 → 0.66

  • Train F1 increased from 0.56 → 0.66

  • Train accuracy improved from 0.51 → 0.62

Reliable validation improvement

  • Val loss decreased from 0.77 → 0.67

  • Val F1 increased from 0.58 → 0.67

  • Val accuracy improved from 0.49 → 0.61

Increased model capacity helped

  • Expanded to 8 convolutional layers with wider channels (32 → 256)

  • The more complex architecture did not benefit the model much. The capping in accuracy maybe limited by the amount of samples

Low learning rate still stable

  • Learning rate at 1e-5 resulted in slower convergence but steady growth

  • Performance improved gradually across all 48 epochs before early stopping triggered

No overfitting observed

  • Val F1 closely tracks train F1 throughout training

  • Slight fluctuations in validation metrics, but trend remains upward and synchronized

Next Step for this model

  • Will consider adding warmup_scheduler to further stabilize the later epoches

  • Increase dropout and fine-tune weight decay to further regularize the model

  • Continue training beyond 60 epochs to see if performance keeps improving or plateaus

  • May consider changing optimizer

Hyperparameter Tuning Trial C [3rd model] (2,000 number of train samples)¶

Amendment

  • Increased number of epochs and have the scheduler_T_Max to match

  • increased dropout to 0.1

  • increased weight decay by 10 times

  • added the warmup_scheduler

  • Optimizer changed from SGD to Adam to see if better optimization performed

# CNN Layer Configuration
CNN_layer_config = {
    'nr_filters': [32, 32, 64, 64, 128, 128, 256, 256],
    'filter_sizes': [3, 3, 3, 3, 3, 3, 3, 3],
    'padding_values': [1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1],
    'stride_values': [1, 2, 1, 2, 1, 2, 1, 2],
    'feature_size': 256 }
               
# Hyperparameters
nr_epoches = 120
dropout = 0.1
weight_decay = 0.00001
learning_rate = 0.00001
scheduler_T_Max = 120
patience = 10

# Initialize model
model = CNN_model(CNN_layer_config,num_classes=len(unique_labels), init_channel=3, input_size=image_shape[0], dropout=dropout).to(device)

# Define Initialization, Loss, Scheduler and Optimizer

criterion = nn.CrossEntropyLoss()
optimizer = torch.optim.Adam(model.parameters(), lr=learning_rate, weight_decay=weight_decay)

warmup_scheduler = torch.optim.lr_scheduler.LambdaLR(optimizer, lr_lambda=lambda epoch: min(1.0, epoch / 5))
scheduler = torch.optim.lr_scheduler.CosineAnnealingLR(optimizer, T_max=scheduler_T_Max)
model1,model_idx,train_losses, val_losses, train_f1_score, val_f1_score = train_and_evaluate_model(model,optimizer,criterion,scheduler,nr_epoches = nr_epoches,early_stopping_patience = patience,warmup_scheduler=warmup_scheduler)

    'feature_size': 256 }

Same architecture as previous models

  • 8-layer CNN with dropout 0.1, weight decay 1e-5 retained

Next Step for this model

  • Consider using more complex CNN architecture

Conclusion on Model 2 (5th model with 160,000 samples)

Rapid and high-quality training progress

  • Train loss decreased from 0.86 → 0.09

  • Train F1 increased from 0.39 → 0.97

  • Train accuracy improved from 0.53 → 0.97

Outstanding validation performance

  • Val loss decreased from 0.78 → 0.11

  • Val F1 increased from 0.43 → 0.96

  • Val accuracy improved from 0.53 → 0.96

Architectural depth and optimizer improvements contributed

  • 10-layer CNN with deeper channel stack (128 → 512) significantly enhanced feature learning

  • Higher learning rate (1e-4) with Adam optimizer accelerated convergence

  • Warm-up and cosine annealing scheduler maintained smooth training updates

  • Early stopping triggered at epoch 33 due to slight plateauing of validation metrics

The model has both high value of training and validation accuracy, which means that the model can generalise the classification to unseen data. It is the best performance model so far.

class InferenceImageDataset(Dataset):
    def __init__(self, image_paths, transform=None):
        self.image_paths = image_paths
        self.transform = transform

    def __len__(self):
        return len(self.image_paths)

    def __getitem__(self, index):
        img_path = self.image_paths[index]
        image = cv2.imread(img_path)
        image = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)
        image = cv2.resize(image, (96, 96), interpolation=cv2.INTER_AREA)
        if self.transform:
            image = self.transform(image)
        return image, os.path.basename(img_path)

results = []
model.eval()
with torch.no_grad():
    for images, filenames in predict_loader:
        images = images.to(device)
        outputs = model(images)
        preds = torch.argmax(outputs, dim=1).cpu().tolist()
        for fname, pred in zip(filenames, preds):
            results.append((fname.split('.')[0], pred))

# Export predictions to CSV

The hyperparameter tuning process progressed through a structured and evidence-driven refinement of both model architecture and training strategy. Starting with a minimal setup and iteratively increasing complexity, each trial provided insight into how model behavior responds to architectural depth, regularization, optimization strategy, and data volume.

  • Increasing model depth and filter width improved feature representation.

  • Switching from SGD to Adam significantly enhanced convergence.

  • Warmup scheduler + CosineAnnealingLR stabilized early and late training stages.

  • Regularization via dropout and weight decay prevented overfitting at deeper scales.

  • Scaling data volume had a major impact on validation generalization.

  • The final model (Model 2) is a strong candidate for deployment with excellent performance and training stability.

5 Conslusion and Take aways¶

Throughout the training and evaluation cycles of multiple CNN architectures, several key findings emerged regarding what contributed to improved model performance and what did not.

Findings on the trial models¶

  • Data Augmentation

It is important technique when dealing with images.

Applying data augmentation techniques such as random rotation, horizontal flipping, and color jitter helped regularize the model and prevented overfitting. These augmentations increased data diversity, making the model more robust to small variations in input.

  • Learning Rate Scheduling with Warmup

The combination of warmup and cosine annealing learning rate scheduling led to smoother convergence and better generalization. It allowed the model to avoid premature convergence and escape local minima early in training.

  • Model Capacity against Dropout & Weight Decay

When increasing the complexity of a model, adding dropout and decay weight regularization helped stabilize training and avoid overfitting. These techniques forced the model to rely less on specific neurons and more on distributed representations.

  • Over-simplified Architectures

Shallow or narrow CNNs underfit the data. They failed to capture the high-dimensional features required to distinguish between subtle malignancy characteristics. The accuracy always stay far below acceptance.

  • Excessive Model Complexity without Regularization

When increasing architecture complexity without proper regularization, the model tended to overfit rapidly. Validation loss would diverge while training loss continued to drop. It is seen in one of the trial model.

  • Training on Imbalanced Full Dataset

Models trained on the imbalanced full training set showed strong bias toward the majority class. The exercie here only extracted subset of the full data, by obtaining equal amount of samples from both labels.

  • High Dropout larger than 0.5

Excessive dropout rates degraded performance due to underutilization of capacity. It limited the model’s ability to learn sufficient feature abstraction. It can be seen in when the train f1 accuracy drops after excessive increase in dropout.

Key Takeaways and Lessons learnt¶

  • Generalization is most improved not by increasing model depth alone, but by balancing dataset, augmenting data, and controlling training dynamics through scheduler and regularization.

  • Validation F1 score is a more reliable metric than accuracy in medical classification tasks, especially with class imbalance.

  • Visualizing training vs validation loss curves is critical to detect overfitting/underfitting early and adjust architecture or regularization accordingly.

  • Saving and restoring the best model based on validation F1 ensures the most generalizable model is retained for inference.
